
Here’s a comprehensive list of SQL query-based interview questions that cover a wide range of SQL topics. You can practice writing queries for each of these questions to improve your SQL skills.

Basic SQL Query Questions
Write a query to retrieve all records from the Employees table.
Write a query to retrieve the distinct job titles from the Employees table.
Write a query to count the number of employees in the Employees table.
Write a query to retrieve all employees whose first name starts with 'A'.
Write a query to retrieve all employees hired in the year 2020.
Write a query to find the maximum salary from the Employees table.
Write a query to find the average salary for employees in the Employees table.
Write a query to delete all employees who are on probation.
Write a query to update the salary of an employee by 10% where the employee's ID is 101.
Write a query to insert a new employee record into the Employees table.
SQL Join Queries
Write a query to retrieve employee details along with their department name using a JOIN.
Write a query to retrieve all employees, including those who are not assigned to a department (use LEFT JOIN).
Write a query to retrieve all departments and the count of employees in each department.
Write a query to get a list of employees who work in the Sales department (use INNER JOIN).
Write a query to get all employees and their managers using a self-join.
Write a query to find all employees who do not belong to any department.
Write a query to retrieve employees whose job title matches those of employees in the HR department.
Write a query to find employees who have the same salary as someone in a different department.
Write a query to find employees who work in both the Marketing and Sales departments (use INTERSECT or EXISTS).
Write a query to get employees who do not belong to the IT department (use EXCEPT or NOT IN).
SQL Subquery Questions
Write a query to find the employee with the second-highest salary using a subquery.
Write a query to retrieve employees whose salary is above the department average salary.
Write a query to find employees whose salaries are greater than the average salary of their managers.
Write a query to find all employees who have a higher salary than the average salary of all employees in the Employees table.
Write a query to get all employees who were hired before a specific employee (use subquery).
Write a query to find employees who earn more than the average salary in their department using a correlated subquery.
Write a query to find all employees who do not have any subordinates.
Write a query to find employees who have the same job title as someone earning more than $50,000.
Write a query to get the name of the department with the most employees.
Write a query to retrieve employees who have the highest salary in their respective departments.
Advanced SQL Query Questions
Write a query to get the running total of salaries for employees ordered by their hire date.
Write a query to calculate the cumulative sum of sales for each day.
Write a query to find the top 3 highest-paid employees in each department.
Write a query to rank employees by their salary within each department.
Write a query to transpose rows to columns using a PIVOT table.
Write a query to calculate the difference between the highest and lowest salaries for each department.
Write a query to find employees who have been in the company for more than 5 years.
Write a query to find employees who have a salary between the average and the highest salary in the company.
Write a query to calculate the monthly sales totals for the current year.
Write a query to find employees who have the same first name but work in different departments.
Performance Tuning and Optimization Query Questions
Write a query to retrieve the last 10 records from a large table with millions of rows.
Write a query to retrieve the top 3 highest-paid employees, but the query should be optimized for performance.
Write a query to count the number of employees without performing a full table scan.
Write a query to retrieve records from a table using indexing efficiently.
Write a query to remove duplicate records from a table without using the ROW_NUMBER() function.
Write an optimized query to retrieve employees based on their department and job title, assuming the table has millions of rows.
Write a query that retrieves employees with a specific job title but executes quickly even when there are millions of records.
Write a query to find the most frequent job title in the Employees table in an optimized way.
Write a query to retrieve employee records from a partitioned table.
Write a query that ensures minimal locking and avoids deadlocks when updating employee records.
Window Functions Query Questions
Write a query to retrieve the rank of employees based on their salary using the RANK() function.
Write a query to retrieve the ROW_NUMBER() for each employee within their department.
Write a query to calculate the running total of salaries using a window function.
Write a query to calculate the cumulative sum of sales using window functions.
Write a query to find the difference between the current and previous employee's salary.
Write a query to retrieve employees along with the difference in their salaries from the department's highest salary.
Write a query to retrieve employees along with their average salary over the last 3 years using window functions.
Write a query to calculate the moving average of employee salaries using window functions.
Write a query to partition employee records by department and rank them by hire date.
Write a query to find the minimum salary in each department using the OVER() clause.
Miscellaneous Query Questions
Write a query to get the first 3 characters of an employee’s first name.
Write a query to concatenate the first and last name of employees.
Write a query to get the difference between two date columns (e.g., how long an employee has been with the company).
Write a query to convert the salary of employees from one currency to another.
Write a query to split a comma-separated string into individual rows.
Write a query to generate a list of years between 2010 and the current year.
Write a query to find employees who have a birthday in the current month.
Write a query to format employee hire dates in MM-DD-YYYY format.
Write a query to delete all records older than 10 years from a table.
Write a query to replace all occurrences of a specific character in a string with another character.
These query-based questions are designed to test your practical knowledge of SQL and your ability to write and optimize queries. They touch on various concepts, from basic operations and joins to advanced topics like window functions and performance tuning.


